message.content:
The command you provided establishes a secure shell (SSH) connection to an Amazon EC2 instance using the specified options:

1. `-i "~/UserKey.pem"`: This option specifies the path to your private SSH key file, which is used for authentication when connecting to the remote server. In this case, it points to a file named "UserKey.pem" located in the user's home directory.

2. `-C`: This option enables compression during the data transfer between the local machine and the remote server. It can help reduce bandwidth usage, especially when transferring large amounts of data.

3. `-L 25900:localhost:5900`: This option sets up a local port forwarding (also known as SSH tunneling). It forwards traffic from the specified local port (25900) on the client machine to the remote server's port (5900) running on `localhost`. This allows you to access a service running on the remote server through the local port.

4. `user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com`: This specifies the username and the hostname or IP address of the Amazon EC2 instance you want to connect to. In this case, it connects to an EC2 instance with the public IP address `34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com` using the 'user' username.

In summary, this command establishes a secure SSH connection to an Amazon EC2 instance, enables compression for data transfer, sets up a local port forwarding from port 25900 on the client machine to port 5900 on the remote server running on `localhost`, and uses the specified private key file for authentication.
